<h3>Alkenes</h3>

<p style="font-family: Arial, sans-serif; line-height: 1.6;">
    Alkenes are unsaturated hydrocarbons containing at least one carbon-carbon double bond (<b>C=C</b>). They are more reactive than alkanes due to the presence of the double bond.
</p>

<h2 style="color: #77dd77; font-family: Arial, sans-serif;">General Formula</h2>
<p style="font-family: Arial, sans-serif; line-height: 1.6;">
    Alkenes follow the general formula <b>C<sub>n</sub>H<sub>2n</sub></b>, where <i>n</i> is the number of carbon atoms. This formula applies only to alkenes with a single double bond and no other functional groups.
</p>

<h2 style="color: #77dd77; font-family: Arial, sans-serif;">Physical Properties</h2>
<ul style="font-family: Arial, sans-serif; line-height: 1.6;">
    <li><b>Boiling Points:</b> Alkenes have boiling points similar to alkanes of comparable molecular weight. Boiling points increase with chain length due to stronger van der Waals forces.</li>
    <li><b>Solubility:</b> Alkenes are insoluble in water but soluble in organic solvents.</li>
</ul>

<h2 style="color: #77dd77; font-family: Arial, sans-serif;">Reactivity of Alkenes</h2>
<p style="font-family: Arial, sans-serif; line-height: 1.6;">
    The double bond in alkenes makes them highly reactive. Common reactions include:
</p>
<ol style="font-family: Arial, sans-serif; line-height: 1.6;">
    <li>
        <b>Electrophilic Addition:</b>
        <ul>
            <li>
                <b>Hydrogenation:</b> Alkenes react with hydrogen in the presence of a nickel catalyst to form alkanes. Example:
                <code>C<sub>2</sub>H<sub>4</sub> + H<sub>2</sub> → C<sub>2</sub>H<sub>6</sub></code>.
            </li>
            <li>
                <b>Halogenation:</b> Alkenes react with halogens (e.g., Br<sub>2</sub>) to form dihalogenoalkanes. Example:
                <code>C<sub>2</sub>H<sub>4</sub> + Br<sub>2</sub> → C<sub>2</sub>H<sub>4</sub>Br<sub>2</sub></code>.
            </li>
            <li>
                <b>Hydration:</b> Alkenes react with steam in the presence of an acid catalyst (e.g., phosphoric acid) to form alcohols. Example:
                <code>C<sub>2</sub>H<sub>4</sub> + H<sub>2</sub>O → C<sub>2</sub>H<sub>5</sub>OH</code>.
            </li>
        </ul>
    </li>
    <li>
        <b>Oxidation:</b> Alkenes are oxidized by potassium manganate (VII) under acidic or alkaline conditions to form diols. Example:
        <code>C<sub>2</sub>H<sub>4</sub> + [O] → CH<sub>2</sub>(OH)CH<sub>2</sub>(OH)</code>.
    </li>
</ol>

<h2 style="color: #77dd77; font-family: Arial, sans-serif;">Tests for Alkenes</h2>
<ul style="font-family: Arial, sans-serif; line-height: 1.6;">
    <li><b>Bromine Water Test:</b> Alkenes decolorize bromine water (orange to colorless), confirming the presence of a double bond.</li>
</ul>

<h2 style="color: #77dd77; font-family: Arial, sans-serif;">Isomerism in Alkenes</h2>
<p style="font-family: Arial, sans-serif; line-height: 1.6;">
    Alkenes exhibit structural and stereoisomerism:
</p>
<ul style="font-family: Arial, sans-serif; line-height: 1.6;">
    <li><b>Structural Isomerism:</b> Different arrangements of the carbon chain or position of the double bond.</li>
    <li><b>Cis-Trans (E/Z) Isomerism:</b> Occurs when there are two different groups attached to each carbon of the double bond. Example: But-2-ene exists as <b>cis-but-2-ene</b> (same side) and <b>trans-but-2-ene</b> (opposite sides).</li>
</ul>

